DREXEL UNIVERSITY PHILANTHROPY JOURNAL 2013



















Welcome Message
Boards of Trustees
We Celebrate
Alumni Relations
Drexel Fund
Campaign Facts & Figures
List of Benefactors
Features

Donors












Celeste & Richard C. Ill '73
“My experience and passions woven through school and work  experience inspired this support for Drexel University. I want to provide  entrepreneurs with educational experiences that can help them be as prepared as  I was for the challenges that lie ahead.”
Chance favored the solidly prepared Richard C. Ill ‘73,  current Chairman of Triumph Group, Inc. and new member of Drexel University’s  board of trustees, throughout his career of hard work, civil service and “luck”  as he humbly points out. The type of luck that happens when one is very, very  prepared and able to spot opportunities where others might not see it. Richard  and his wife Celeste, are generously giving back in a way inspired by Richard’s  career, and are helping Drexel’s entrepreneurs create their own “luck.”
    	          Richard, who was named Regional Award Winner: An  Entrepreneur of the Year and a runner up on the national level by Ernst &  Young in 2009, has been highly recognized for his innovative and leading  talents in the complex aerospace industry. Upon stepping down as CEO he found  himself with the focused time and financial ability to give back. Giving to  entrepreneurial education through Drexel’s Laurence A. Baiada Institute for  Entrepreneurship—part of the Charles D. Close School of  Entrepreneurship—provides student entrepreneurs with programs integral to  exploring their ideas in real world situations, the foundation for solid  preparation to make invention happen. Richard and Celeste’s gift generously  provides insider access including: business incubation, subject matter experts,  company mentoring, participation in annual business plan competitions and  access to entrepreneurial conferences—all forwarding cooperative  entrepreneurial education at Drexel University. These opportunities will  provide students with the tools they need to build, compete and lead in a  highly competitive world. They will be prepared to find opportunities and  fearlessly go forward with their ideas. 
    	          As a Drexel MBA student in the early 1970s, Richard—freshly  back from serving as a captain in the US Army—completed his master’s degree  over five packed years of work and school at Drexel’s College of Business  Administration. Fresh out of the Army Richard landed a mail clerk job at the  former Alco Standard, a company that served the chemical, electrical,  metallurgical, and distribution industries. His employment experience at Alco  informed his studies and his studies influenced his rapidly developing career.  Open communication with his teachers and an early disagreement with a professor  over whether you can market more then one product with one company brand became  a topic for a thesis: Marketing within the Multi-Products Company. Richard was  certain it could be done. Ironically, that is what Triumph, the aerospace  branch of the former conglomerate at Alco came to be under Richard’s  leadership. His personal and professional engagements in the Army, work and  school fostered people skills, bringing manpower and ideas together, while  serving him and his employees well. “My experience and passions woven through  school and work experience inspired this support for Drexel University.” states  Richard. “I want to provide entrepreneurs with educational experiences that can  help them be as prepared as I was for the challenges that lie ahead.”
   	            In gratitude for Richard and Celeste’s generosity Drexel has  named the Celeste and Richard Ill Incubator for Entrepreneurial and  Experiential Education after them. A plaque will adorn the entrance of this  main room on Drexel’s brand new LeBow College of Business’s main floor  laboratory, celebrating their generous gift that will create chances for our  prepared entrepreneurs.








